	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes2.html?class=8&mid=101805163075971>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes2.html?class=8&mid=101805163075971>RE: MONEY...or lack of</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes2.html?class=8&mid=101805163075971#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Apr 5th 7:11 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=151942><span id=Guru>Kelanthor</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>159 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Hi there,<br><br>Well, you're probably close enough to lvl 29 to follow Dirnle's advice, but you could try making a few PP through tradeskills. I've been working on mine since early levels and they now provide a small but steady income.<br><br>I make fish rolls with the Baking skill and they pull in at least 5pp a stack - my skill is high enough now that I succeed 85% of the time or more. Monks and low-STR types love these, as they only weigh 2lb per stack and each one is a 'banquet' meal. Means you only need to scoff one every 90 minutes or so.<br><br>Tailoring is the other money-spinner. Ruined pelts make patchwork armour (I hardly ever fail now) that sells back to the vendor for over double what the pattern cost. Low-quality pelts can be turned into pouches and bags with weight-reducing capabilities. Large bags sell for anything between 15 and 30pp. I only ever ask for 15, but some hi-lvl folk stump up extra at the trade. Bless 'em! Raw and cured silk armour sells well to monks, although I'm not succeeding enough with cured yet to turn a profit. The best thing is, being a Druid, this skill will provide armour for you as your skill increases (although you're probably past the stage of using the stuff you can make at the start). Finally, once your skill gets up in the 70s (not there yet!) you can start making the backpacks - 10 giant slots, 10% weight reduction. These go for 90 - 100pp on my server (Mithaniel Marr) and should provide good income.<br><br>Smithing and Brewing are just being used to support the other trades at the mo, although I want to work Smithing up so I can make banded armour - another money-spinner!<br><br>While I've had my share of gifts from helpful hi-lvl folk (Flint Hammer, Shiny Brass Shield) I've also earned enough to upgrade most of my kit to some form of magic - Foreman's Tunic, Spore-Covered Helm, Sleeves and Cloak, +WIS earrings and rings. My only non-magical armour is my Studded Shoulderpads and Boots. I am non-twinked, this is my first character on EQ, I have all spells for my lvl and about 300pp in the bank.<br><br>I dunno if this is any help to you, Lindarie, but it'll mebbe help out others at lower levels. Perhaps you should power-lvl to 29 and then make your dosh from gate spells, as Dirnle suggests. Whichever way you go, the main point is to have fun - I enjoy the tradeskill side of EQ, others prefer non-stop hack n slash! To each their own...<br><br>Good hunting!</p>&nbsp;<br>Kelanthor<br>Wood Elf Wanderer of the 53rd Circle<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672</a><br>"It's only the giving that makes you what you are..."</td></tr>
