<tr><td colspan=2><ul>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f101889525953352>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes2.html?class=8&mid=101889525953352>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes2.html?class=8&mid=101889525953352>RE: New One</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes2.html?class=8&mid=101889525953352#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Apr 15th 2:33 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=106454><span id= >Lunarwolf</span></a><br><span id=notbold>18 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Let's see....druid...bard...cleric.&nbsp;&nbsp;I have two out of the three, so I'll tell you what I think<br><br>Druid - Druids are a really nice class.  At low levels, they serve well in a melee form with back-up burns.  In the middle levels (20-33) you're still pretty powerful.  You have a good combination of burns, heals, DS's and buffs to keep everyone in the group alive and happy.  I think druid's are an invaluable resource during these levels, and you should take advantage of this to make a lot of friends, which you're gonna need for the high levels (34-60).  From here, druids, in my opinion, kinda peter out from groups.  Druid become what I think of as a utility class.  They're good at a lot of things in groups, but don't really do any one thing well.  Need a healer?  I can do that.  Like nukers?  that too.  Snare and root?  no problem.  But we dont do any of those, cept maybe snare/root, as well as the classes that were made for them.  So, sometime's its hard to find a group unless the group can't find a REAL healer/nuker/etc.<br><br>Bards - this is a class made for people who just can't sit still.  If you have ADHD, this is just the class for you.  Bards are easy to play, but very hard to play well.  They have a nice mix of everything, healing/nuking/DD/DoT/AC buff/Str Buff/haste/charm/fear...the list goes on.  I think that bards are ALWAYS a strong class to have in a group, although people who do not understand how bards work may not like having them around.  They also have a good ability to kite and solo through many levels of the game.  <br><br>Clerics - Clerics are a powerful low level class.  With the ability to throw on some plate, get in some good damage, and heal everyone around, you can't go without them.  I think that the lack of offensive spells in the mid-game weakens their performance a little, however, not many groups can go far, fast, without a cleric.  You'll find yourself sitting and medding a lot throughout the game, but you have to do that to do your job, which is keeping people alive.  You'll have to learn aggro management at an early age to stay alive.  High end clerics are amazing, indispensible on raids and for much daily EQ'ing.  If you dont play a cleric, find one and be their friend.  Free Advice:  Be aware that as you get rez spells, it is YOUR responsibility that you dont die.  Its hard for some people to make the transition of 'Fight to the Death' to 'Camp out and rez us after we die...'<br><br>Races<br>I personally dont think that race has much to do with a lot here in the game.  There is enough stat enhancing gear that a few less wis in the beginning wont make much of a difference in the end.  So play which race you like.  Ive always been a fan of Fadwyer races, so my druid is a Wood Elf, but I do think that a Halfling makes a good choice also.  I wanted a change, so my bard and monk are both human.  Finally, I see a lot of Dwarf and High Elf clerics running around, and I really want to see a Dark Elf cleric, so think about it.<br><br>I hope this was somewhat helpful.<br><br>Lunar</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
